Now that the festivities announced in 27 f. are on the way and that a neat compliment to Messalla has been turned, the poet proceeds with his next topic, the formal announcement of which is ‘ rura cano rurisque deos) In the lines which follow he again displays his surpassing gift of concealing the utmost care and skill of development under the garb of unstudied sim· plicity. As usual, too, the theme was already well worn. Lines 35-36 serve, while paying another compliment to Messalla, as the transition.

36. agricolis: the reference is purposely indefinite and the word returns to its rare adjectival use, see 1, r, 14; 1, 5, 27 and notes.
